'''Sir Anthony John Patrick Kenny ''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FBA}} (born 16 March 1931) is an [[English people|English]] [[philosopher]] whose interests lie in the [[philosophy of mind]], [[ancient philosophy|ancient]] and [[Scholasticism|scholastic]] philosophy, the philosophy of [[Ludwig Wittgenstein|Wittgenstein]] and the [[philosophy of religion]]. With [[Peter Geach]], he has made a significant contribution to [[Analytical Thomism]], a movement whose aim is to present the thought of St. [[Thomas Aquinas]] in the style of [[analytic philosophy]]. He is one of the executors of Wittgenstein's [[literary estate]]. He is a former President of the [[British Academy]] and the [[Royal Institute of Philosophy]].

==Education and early career==
Kenny initially trained as a [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] [[priest]] at the [[Venerable English College]], [[Rome]], where he received a degree of [[Licentiate of Sacred Theology]] (STL) degree. He was ordained in 1955 and served as a curate in Liverpool (1959–63). Having received his [[Doctor of Philosophy|DPhil]] from the [[University of Oxford]] ([[St Benet's Hall, Oxford|St Benet's Hall]]) in 1961, he also worked as an assistant lecturer at the [[University of Liverpool]] (1961–63). However, he questioned the validity of Roman Catholic doctrine and is now an agnostic.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}} He was returned to the lay state in 1963, but according to [[Canon law (Catholic Church)|canon law]] his priestly ordination remains valid. He was never dispensed from the obligation of clerical celibacy and was therefore [[excommunicate]]d on his marriage to Nancy Gayley in 1965.<ref>''What I Believe'', ch. 1.</ref>

==Academic career==
During 1963-64, Kenny was lecturer in Philosophy at [[Exeter College, Oxford|Exeter]] and [[Trinity College, Oxford|Trinity]] Colleges, Oxford and he served as University Lecturer 1965–78. From 1964 until 1978, he was a Fellow of [[Balliol College, Oxford]] and Senior Tutor during the periods 1971–72 and 1976–78. He was [[Master (college)|Master]] of Balliol from 1978 to 1989 and subsequently an Honorary Fellow. During the period 1989–99, he was both [[Warden (college)|Warden]] of [[Rhodes House]] (manager of the [[Rhodes Scholarship]] program) and Professorial Fellow of [[St John's College, Oxford|St John's College]] and thereafter Fellow [[Emeritus]]. He was [[Pro-Vice-Chancellor]] of the [[University of Oxford]] from 1984 to 2001 (Pro-Vice-Chancellor for Development, 1999–2001). He retired in 2001.

Within the university, Kenny was Wilde Lecturer in Natural and Comparative Religion (1969–72), Speaker's Lecturer in Biblical Studies (1980–83), a member of the Hebdomadal Council (1981–93), Vice-Chairman of the Libraries Board (1985–88), Curator of the [[Bodleian Library]] (1985–88) and a Delegate, and member of the Finance Committee, of [[Oxford University Press]] (1986–93). From 1972 until 1973 he was the editor of ''[[The Oxford Magazine]]''. He received the degree of [[Doctor of Letters|DLitt]] in 1980 and the honorary degree of [[Doctor of Civil Law|DCL.]] in 1987.

He was a member of the Board of the [[British Library]] 1991-96 and Chairman 1993-96, and has served as Chairman of the Society for Protection of Science and Learning (1989–93), of the British National Corpus Advisory Board (1990–95), of the British Irish Association (1990–94), and of the Board of the [[Warburg Institute]] (1996–2000). He was elected a Fellow of the [[British Academy]] in 1974 and served as a member of the Council of the Academy 1985-88, as Vice President 1986-88 and President 1989-93.

Kenny was Gifford Lecturer at the [[University of Edinburgh]] 1972-73 and at the [[University of Glasgow]] in 1988, Stanton Lecturer at the [[University of Cambridge]] 1980-83, and [[Bampton Lectures (Columbia University)|Bampton Lecturer at Columbia University]] in 1983. He was a Visiting Professor at [[University of Chicago|Chicago]], [[University of Washington|Washington]], [[University of Michigan|Michigan]], [[University of Minnesota|Minnesota]], [[Cornell University|Cornell]], [[Stanford University|Stanford]] and [[Rockefeller University|Rockefeller]] Universities.

He has been a member of the American Philosophical Society since 1993, and of the [[Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]] since 1993, and an Honorary Fellow of [[Harris Manchester College, Oxford]] since 1996, and of the [[School of Advanced Study|School of Advanced Study, University of London]] since 2002 (Senior Distinguished Fellow 2002-3). He has received the honorary degrees of [[Doctor of Letters|D.Litt.]] from [[University of Bristol|Bristol]] (1982), [[University of Liverpool|Liverpool]] (1988), [[University of Glasgow|Glasgow]] (1990), [[Trinity College, Dublin]] (1992), [[University of Hull|Hull]] (1993), [[University of Sheffield|Sheffield]] (1995), and [[University of Warwick|Warwick]] (1995), of [[Doctorate|D.Hum.Litt.]] from [[Denison University]], Ohio (1986) and [[Lafayette College]], Pennsylvania (1990) and of [[Doctor of Civil Law|D.C.L.]] from the [[Queen's University of Belfast]] (1994).

==Honours and awards==
Kenny was made a [[Knight Bachelor]] by [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom]] in 1992 and has been an Honorary Bencher of [[Lincoln's Inn]] since 1999.

In October 2006, Kenny was awarded the American Catholic Philosophical Association's Aquinas Medal for his significant contributions to philosophy.

Portraits of Kenny hang in the [[British Academy]], London, and at [[Balliol College]] and [[Rhodes House]], Oxford.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/six-academy-presidents-gallus-gallus-with-still-life-and-215017 BBC website.]</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1397582.stm https://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/sir-anthony-kenny-fellow-and-tutor-in-philosophy-19641978221625 BBC website.]</ref>

==Philosophy==
Although deeply interested in traditional Catholic teaching and continuing to attend the [[Catholic Mass]],<ref>[[William C. Dowling]], "Meaningless grades and a new dishonesty", Springer New York, Volume 16, Number 4 / September, 2003</ref> Kenny now explicitly defines himself as an [[Agnosticism|agnostic]], explaining in his ''What I believe'' both why he is not a theist and why he is not an atheist. His 2006 book ''What I believe'' has (as Ch 3) "Why I am Not an Atheist", which begins: "Many different definitions may be offered of the word 'God'. Given this fact, atheism makes a much stronger claim than theism does. The atheist says that no matter what definition you choose, 'God exists' is always false. The theist only claims that there is some definition which will make 'God exists' true. In my view, neither the stronger nor the weaker claim has been convincingly established". He goes on: "the true default position is neither theism nor atheism, but agnosticism ... a claim to knowledge needs to be substantiated; ignorance need only be confessed."<ref>''What I Believe'', ch. 3</ref> He defends the rationality of an agnostic praying to a God whose existence he doubts, stating "It surely is no more unreasonable than the act of a man adrift in the ocean, trapped in a cave, or stranded on a mountainside, who cries for help though he may never be heard or fires a signal which may never be seen."<ref>Kenny 1979, p. 129</ref> This view is kin to [[Christian agnosticism]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2016}}

Kenny has written extensively on [[Thomas Aquinas]] and modern [[Thomism]]. In ''The Five Ways'', Kenny deals with St. Thomas' five proofs of God. In it, Kenny argues that none of the proofs Thomas sets out are wholly valid, and instead sets out to show the flaws in the five ways. His arguments range from the problem of Aristotelian motion in a modern scientific context, to the ability of contingent beings to cause eternality in other contingent beings. His objections all focus on a modern interpretation of St. Thomas.

Kenny candidly describes the predicament of the beginning of the universe, which both atheists and agnostics face, writing, "According to the Big Bang Theory, the whole matter of the universe began at a particular time in the remote past. A proponent of such a theory, at least if he is an atheist, must believe that the matter of the universe came from nothing and by nothing."<ref>Anthony Kenny, The Five Ways: St. Thomas Aquinas' Proofs of God's Existence (New York: Schocken, 1969), p. 66</ref>

In ''What is Faith?'', Kenny addresses "the question of whether belief in God, and faith in a divine world, is a reasonable or rational state of mind."<ref>''What is Faith?'', p. 3</ref>  He criticises the idea, "common to theists like [[Aquinas]] and [[Descartes]] and to an atheist like [[Bertrand Russell|Russell]]," that "Rational belief [is] either self-evident or based directly or indirectly on what is evident," which he terms "foundationalism" following [[Alvin Plantinga|Plantinga]],<ref>''What is Faith?'', pp. 9–10</ref> arguing out that foundationalism is a [[self-refuting idea]].

