{{Other uses|Gosei (disambiguation){{!}}Gosei}}
[[Image:Gosei1.jpg|thumb|right|Five Reflections.]]

{{nihongo|'''Gosei'''|五省|go-sei|''lit., five reflections''}} are subjects for daily meditation at Japan's Naval Academy.

==Five Reflections==

These reflections were originally devised by Vice Admiral [[Hajime Matsushita]], who was the Chief of the [[Imperial Japanese Naval Academy]] , and used from 1932 to its abolishment in 1945. Every evening cadets are expected to meditate on these inter-related questions.<ref>Smith, Peter C. (2006). {{Google books|ma1teOqjMNQC|''Fist from the Sky: Japan's Dive-Bomber Ace of World War II,'' p. 63.|page=63}}</ref>
# {{nihongo|Hast thou not gone against sincerity|至誠に悖る勿かりしか}}
# {{nihongo|Hast thou not felt ashamed of thy words and deeds|言行に恥づる勿かりしか}}
# {{nihongo|Hast thou not lacked vigor|気力に缺くる勿かりしか}}
# {{nihongo|Hast thou exerted all possible efforts|努力に憾み勿かりしか}}
# {{nihongo|Hast thou not become slothful|不精に亘る勿かりしか}}

The [[Japan Maritime Self Defense Force]] (JMSDF), from its establishment in 1954, encourages the use of the ''Gosei'' as a self-reflective exercise during the course of daily living.

The crux of this contemplative practice has been translated into English and has been discussed at the [[United States Naval Academy]].<ref>Kennedy, Maxwell T. (2009). {{Google books|SAbIZK2hJLwC|''Danger's Hour,'' p. 91.|page=91}}</ref>

