{{about||the Polish band|Kobong (band)}} {{Infobox religious biography |background = #FFD068 | color = black |name = Kobong / 고봉 / 高峯 |image = Ko Bong.jpg |caption = |birth name = |alias = |dharma name = |birth_date = 1890 |birth_place = [[Korea]] |death_date = 1962 |death_place = |nationality = |religion = [[Jogye Order|Chogye]] ([[Korean Buddhism#Seon|Seon]]) |school = |lineage = |title = [[Zen master]] |location = |education = |occupation = |teacher = |reincarnation of = |predecessor = [[Man-gong]] |successor = [[Seungsahn]] |students = |spouse = |partner = |children = |website = }} {{Infobox Korean name | hangul = 고봉 | hanja = 古峰 | rr = Gobong | mr = Kobong | hangulborn = 박경욱 | hanjaborn = 朴景昱 | rrborn = Bak Gyeonguk | mrborn = Pak Kyŏnguk }}
'''Kobong''' ''soensanim'' ([[Korean language|Korean]]: 고봉선사, [[Hanja]]: 高峯禪師, 1890–1962),<ref name="sweepingzen">{{cite web|title=Ko Bong|url=http://sweepingzen.com/zm-ko-bong-bio/|publisher=Sweeping Zen|accessdate=April 16, 2013}}</ref><ref name="chogyesa">{{cite web|title=Ko Bong Sunim|url=http://www.nychogyesa.org/chogyesa_teachers_KoBong.html|publisher=Chogyesa Zen Temple of New York|accessdate=April 16, 2013}}</ref> the 77th Patriarch in his teaching lineage, was a [[Korean people|Korean]] [[Zen Teacher/Zen Master|Zen master]].
==Biography== At an early age, Kobong became a monk at [[Namjangsa]].<ref name="chogyesa"/> Known for spontaneous and eccentric teaching,<ref name="sweepingzen"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Korean Zen: Ko Bong|url=http://www.oxherding.com/my_weblog/2009/04/korean-zen-ko-bong.html|publisher=Ox Herding|accessdate=April 16, 2013}}</ref> he sometimes said that he preferred to teach laypeople because [[Bhikku|monks]] were too lazy to practice hard.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ko Bong’s Try Mind|url=http://www.kwanumzen.org/1996/ko-bongs-try-mind/|publisher=Kwan Um School of Zen|accessdate=April 16, 2013}}</ref><ref name="musangsa">{{cite web|title=Zen Master Ko Bong|url=http://www.musangsa.org/english/sub02/sub02_3.php|publisher=Mu Sang Sa|accessdate=April 16, 2013}}</ref>
Kobong never held a position at any temple or established a temple of his own.<ref name="flower">{{cite web|title=Flower Valley Temple The Story of Hwa Gye Sah|url=http://www.kwanumzen.org/1998/flower-valley-temple-the-story-of-hwa-gye-sah/|publisher=|accessdate=April 16, 2013}}</ref> When he was elderly, his student [[Seungsahn]] brought him to [[Hwagyesa]]<ref name="flower"/> in [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]] where Kobong died at the temple in 1962.<ref name="musangsa"/> A large granite monument was built in his honor on the hillside overlooking Hwagyesa.
==Lineage== Kobong Sunim was [[Dharma transmission|Dharma heir]] to [[Mangong]] Sunim, who was in turn Dharma heir to [[Kyongho]] Sunim. Kobong Sunim's best known student was [[Seungsahn]] Sunim (1927–2004), founder of the [[Kwan Um School of Zen]]. Seungsahn Sunim received Dharma transmission from Kobong Sunim at 22 years of age. Kobong had never given [[Dharma transmission|inka]] to any monk before he met Seungsahn Sunim<ref name="chogyesa"/> and Seungsahn remained his only dharma heir.<ref name="musangsa"/>
Sunim is a Korean word that means ordained Buddhist and can refer to both men and women who have taken ordination vows.
