'''Konrad Talmont-Kamiński''' (born 1 January 1971 in [[Chojnice]], [[Poland]]{{r|cv}}) is an [[Analytic philosophy|analytic]] philosopher and [[cognitive scientist]], dealing with [[epistemology]], [[philosophy of science]], [[philosophy of mind]] and the theory of [[rationality]].{{r|OBF|esc17|bio-loop|whoami}} His work is also influenced by [[psychology]], [[biology]], history, [[anthropology]] and other disciplines.{{r|OBF|whoami}}

He obtained his [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in History and [[Philosophy of Science]] from the [[University of Melbourne]] in [[Melbourne]] in 1994, his [[Master of Arts|MA]] from the [[University of Western Ontario]] in [[London, Ontario]], Canada in 1995, and his doctorate from [[Monash University]] in [[Melbourne]]{{r|kli-bio}} in 1999, under the supervision of John Bigelow, PhD{{r|OBF}} He then moved to [[Poland]] in 2001,{{r|esc17}} where he first worked for the [[Polish Academy of Science]], and later in the [[Maria Curie-Skłodowska University]] in [[Lublin]],{{r|OBF}} the [[Warsaw University of Finance and Management]] in [[Warsaw]], Psychology Department,{{r|whoami}} and [[University of Białystok]] in [[Białystok]].{{r|bio-loop}} He publishes in journals such as ''[[The Monist]]'', ''Frontiers in Psychology and Religion'', ''[[Brain and Behavior]]'',{{r|esc17}} and ''[[Skeptical Inquirer]] magazine.''{{r|csi|si}}

During his scholarship at the [[Konrad Lorenz Institute for Evolution and Cognition Research]] in Vienna, [[Austria]] he began working on the cognitive basis of [[supernatural]] beliefs ([[superstitions]], [[Magic (paranormal)|magic]], and religion).{{r|esc17|whoami}} The work resulted in a book published in 2014 ''Religion as a Magical Ideology: How the Supernatural Reflects Rationality'',{{r|religion-magical|esc17|bio-loop}} for which he received his habilitation in 2014.{{r|bio-loop}} He also presents his works in many conferences in Australia and Europe. He will be a speaker at the [[European Skeptics Congress#17th European Skeptics Congress|17th European Skeptics Congress]] in [[Wrocław]], [[Poland]], where he will give a speech: ''Cognition and the Science/Religion Debate''.{{r|esc17|esc-youtube}}

His current interests are the [[empirical]] implications of the model proposed in the book, connecting [[ritual]]ised behaviour with [[superstition]],{{r|esc17}} and the development of a broadly [[Peircean]] account of [[reason]].{{r|kli-bio}}

